metadata.label: Transcript
metadata.value: THE writer has been in charge of the publicly-owned railroad and terminals in  Charleston for three and a half years  and during that time has had opportuntiy to  investigate all the ports on the West Coast,  all on the Gulf Coast and all South of  Boston on the East Coast, and this article  shall be an attempt to show interested  parties, the conditions that apparently surround all of the municipal and public ventures.  In the Port of Charleston, there has been  a struggle for eighty years to understand  the transportation problem with particular  reference to the railroads and terminals for  steamships. But in that long period there  has never been evolved any policy of port  operation or port organization that met the  popular approval or the approval of the  business men. The attempt to aid the port,  resulting in the construction of the Memphis  to Charleston Railroad in the fifties was the  proposed solution by the farsighted men of  those times, and had it been completed,  would have undoubtedly placed Charleston  in a prominent situation for all time.  It failed because of financial difficulties  and left its lasting imprint on Charleston's  development by a burden of debt and the  destruction of the public's confidence in such  ventures.  As a result, Charleston left its port to  grow or languish as conditions developed.  And these conditions were controlled by  other forces than those interested in the  Port of Charleston.  The railroads of this country have gone  through periods of prosperity and periods  of depression,and have gone through varied  policies of operation. "The public be  damned" was rampant at one time, and the  record seems to reveal that at no time were  the railroads interested in all ports equally  and alike.  The record does not reveal that any of the  communities were able to work out a policy  or a program to enter the fight to secure  their rights. Many have been the plans  tried and the failures almost as numerous.  Ports have thrived and decayed depending  on the artificial stimulation or depression of  traffic.  The Port of Charleston went through a  long, hard struggle to have its natural advantages recognized and with some success,  fmt'the net result has not developed a policy.  It has furnished, however, a background on  which to base a sound constructive policy  provided the proper agency is available to  formulate such a policy.  PORT ORGANIZATION  Requires a Fixed Definite Policy that is  Based on Business Principles  It is a fact easily established that the  operation of the ports is highly profitable  to certain individuals engaged in specific  port services, but due to railroad competitive practices a gradual operation of terminals on an unremunerative basis has become  the accepted  practice.  The writer in Nineteen Hundred and  Twenty-Five was told by the vice president of a large railroad: "Railroad operation at the ports is costly. All interests  demand costly services and our railroad is  forced to operate in the ports at a loss."  At the last hearings on Port Charges  Docket No. 12681 practically all the Southern Carriers endorsed the policy of remunerative terminal charges, and this result was  obtained largely by the intelligent efforts of  private and public rail-water terminal opera-  tors,and the weight of the public, state, and  municipal operators' demands made itself  apparent and was felt and undoubtedly  influenced the attitude of the railroads.  Through it all, however, it is apparent  that the ports are not organized as they must  ultimately be, and opportunity was offered  to observers to witness the many and varied  policies being followed in the various ports.  There has crept in most of the Municipal  Ports, a demand that port development requires that the community make a contribution for that purpose, and a close analysis  of thinking citizens convinces the writer  that this sentiment is the result of the  demands of waterfront operators that their  rates be lower, "to bring new business" or  "to meet competition," or to "prevent the  business going to Savannah or Pensacola."  Further analysis of the average citizen  convinces me that he does not believe that  an outside waterfront operator should have  any unfair advantage over local operators,  and if the Municipal Property is honestly  managed, then the local operators should  receive similar concessions, and when this is  done, it becomes a policy of operation resulting in a deficit. And then agitation  starts for efficiency and business operation,  and the cycle is gone through and the organization is swept out by politics and  friends, relatives, and theorists take charge  and again go through the cycle. At the  same time, it is costing the average taxpayer  money, and as a policy cannot be justified.  These conditons have resulted in similar  practices at other neighboring and competitive ports, and the net result is, that port  terminal operation has gotten down to a  costly basis- It is impossible to collect  dockage from a ship, it is impossible to  collect legitimate storage on cargo because  some operator next door leases space at an  advantage; it is impossible to collect full  wharfage, because some operator has cut it  off or reduced it; and handling charges  vary from zero to as little as such competition may enable operation to collect.  There is one phase of this terminal prob  lem that has been developed by large importers of staple commodites. At their  headquarters in New York, they decide to  import to C. F. A. territory a large tonnage  of their commodity. They send out a representative for rates and by shrewd methods  the competition of the port is taken advantage of and the tonnage moves through the  lowest port. As an example of what this  costs, witness the statistics of the Savannah  situation where the three railroads there  operating 15,000,000 of rail-water property  showed losses of 11,140,000 at those properties for 1924. These losses are a true  measure of what the competing municipal  or public dock must face in order to meet  the competition.  Therefore, it is evident to any observer,  that a definite port program and policy is  necessary and it should be handled by a  group, free from politics and influences that  are selfish. Its construction programs should  be based on the ability of the business to  pay the overhead and the community should  endorse and follow the leadership of this  unbiased group.  Unfortunately, such an operation is not  the usual practice. Rather the reverse is  true. Administration follows administration, and the charges destroy the chance of  a trained organization strong enough to  combat selfish interests.  In general, the port organization should  be centralized  around the actual  facilities.  There is no other policy free of the possibility of conflict between those who want  the tonnage at any cost, and then those who  are responsible for deficits that result from  such a policy.  In this respect, the railroads are in the  same situation. Their traffic officials are  bent on tonnage development by free time  on cars, by lower rates, and other similar  practices; on the other hand, the operating  men are endeavoring to haul the freight  faster and farther and at less cost, and these  two policies conflict.  It is absolutely necessary for the port organization to know the public opinion as  to the policy to follow, and there is always  the possibility of having pressure brought to  bear on those administering the policy.  All the ports have gone through and are  going through the stage of dissatisfaction  with the public ownership. In general this  has been caused by the mismanagement and  the lack of a policy on the part of those in  charge, but it is evident that the public is  not disposed to have the public funds given  promiscuously to those favored individuals  who are aggressively using the public property.  Errors in construction programs resulting  in overbuilding facilities to an extent where  the overhead carrying charges exceed the  possibility of the earnings paying them results in loss of confidence on the part of  the public.  No construction advocates should be in a  position to burden port operation over the  future, because he failed to face the solid  business competitive situation that makes  his construction program a community burden. Rather should the commission controlling his acts be responsible for the policy  under which the new work is developed.  In conclusion, it is perfectly evident to  any thinking individual that each community must have its agency for regulation and  control of the vital factors of rail-water  transportation. Its rights and interests are  not to be protected by selfishly inclined individuals. Its assets of geographical advantages and favorable climate should not  be considered the birthright of a few but  rather conserved by the community or state  for the use of all on an equal basis.  It is a business pure and simple and  should be handled as a business and free  from influences and in this respect politics,  that portion of them that give the spoils to  the favored few should have no possible  place in the operation.
